;; kekkai-tailnet.edn.example — the murakumo fleet-admission ledger (kekkai gate).
;;
;; Copy this to ./kekkai-tailnet.edn (gitignored — it's local operational state,
;; like .murakumo-peers.edn) to OPT IN to the zero-trust admission gate: once
;; present, `murakumo.fleet/select` (and every command built on it — nodes,
;; provision, status, mesh, deploy, up/down) only operates on nodes whose entry
;; here has :status "authorized". A node merely listed in fleet.edn but absent
;; or non-"authorized" here is excluded and reported to stderr — being in the
;; desired inventory is not enough (that would make the governor a no-op).
;;
;; This is the same shape kotoba-lang/kekkai's Store expects (kekkai.store/
;; demo-data's :nodes). Real admission (moving a node from "pending" to
;; "authorized") happens through kekkai's own CoordinationActor — a coord-LLM
;; proposal, censored by TailnetGovernor, with node admission ALWAYS routed to
;; a human (kekkai.governor's :node/admit high-stakes rule). This file is the
;; resulting ground-fact snapshot murakumo consults; it does not run the
;; admission flow itself. See kotoba-lang/kekkai/README.md.
{:nodes
 {"naphtali" {:id "naphtali" :status "authorized" :did "did:key:zNaphtali"}
  "simeon"   {:id "simeon"   :status "authorized" :did "did:key:zSimeon"}
  ;; a newly added Mac mini stays "pending" (excluded from fleet ops) until an
  ;; operator explicitly admits it through kekkai — adding a fleet.edn line
  ;; alone does not grant it trust.
  "judah"    {:id "judah"    :status "pending"    :did "did:key:zJudah"}}}
